Vietnam Bonds Decline on Speculation Investors Favoring Stocks

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-09-19T08:46:38Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-19/vietnam-bonds-decline-on-speculation-investors-favoring-stocks.html
Vietnam ’s three-year bonds fell on
speculation investors are favoring shares over fixed-income
securities as the local stock market surges.  The Ho Chi Minh City Stock Exchange’s VN Index rose 1
percent to 461.68 today, taking its advance to more than 20
percent from a 27-month low on Aug. 12. Commercial banks cut
lending rates for some borrowers to as low as 16 percent last
week from more than 20 percent, according to a statement on the
central bank’s website. Consumer prices increased 23 percent in
August from a year earlier, the most since November 2008.  “Investors have decided to switch to other investment
channels, such as stocks, to get higher returns and offset
losses due to the high inflation,” ACB Securities Inc. said in
a note to clients obtained today.  Three-year yields rose three basis points, or 0.03
percentage point, to 12.38 percent, according to a daily fixing
from banks compiled by Bloomberg.  The dong strengthened 0.1 percent today to 20,817 per
dollar as of 3:40 p.m. in Hanoi, according to prices from banks.
The central bank set the  reference rate  at 20,628, unchanged
since Aug. 24, its website showed. The currency is allowed to
trade up to 1 percent on either side of the official rate.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Sandy Hendry at 
 shendry@bloomberg.net  